questionRound.0.question.9.answer: There is a way to determine the maximum amount of money everyone in the match can get.  The first player is the only person who can really suffer.  Whatever the first player chooses  the last player will choose the choice that maximizes their own personal profit. Most of the players in the game know this.  As such  based on the first person's decision  everyone in the game can infer the last person's decision.  And if you know what the last person will choose  you yourself (depending on how close you are to the end of the turns) will choose whatever maximizes your own personal profit.  Based on these  assuming everyone knows that the last person will choose for their own profit  you can infer the best decision to make without the most loss.

It depended on which role I was assigned. If I was going first I took the highest option I had and went to the last square and worked my way back to the beginning backwards to see how everyone would choose. If I went last I just chose the highest value I could get based on what the first person had chosen.
The decision for the right most player was easy. So building on that and making reverse decisions assuming that every player wants to win the maximum amount.
Try to get as much as possible  assuming that everyone would do the same and be selfish

Assume other players are logical and seeking to maximize their own payout.  Select the row which will give me a larger payout based on the predicted column that the related player would choose -- working backwards from my own selection do this for each player to predict which column of my payout matrix would be selected

I was basically just looking forward and reasoning back  something I learned in the game theory portion of my microeconomics course. Since I was the first player only twice throughout the entire experiment  I didn't have to look too much forward to decide X or Y.

If I were the first player then i would look at what the last player would choose and work backwords through all the other players from there until i got to the second player which would tell me if my decision would give me the highest payoff. If i was the last player i would choose the highest of the two that coresponded to the answer chosen by the first player. if i was in the middle I would look at the other player s decision.

I think of what the choices people will make backward  since what one player's payoff is depends on the next person's move.  And if I was the first player  I act out two options and see which one generates higher payoff.  That's the choice I will make then.

If I was the first to choose  it's all about working backwards; I hypothetically in my head go through both options of  | choosing x or y. Then  I would go to the box on the far right and see what that person would choose if I chose either x or y. Then I would see what the person to the left of the farthest to the right would choose. I will keep doing this until  I  | come back to my own box all the way on the left and see if it would give me the higher number of the lower number in the row. One of my choices  either x or y  would lead to me having the highest number and everybody having the highest number they could considering the conditions. If I was at the right  I would choose whichever gave me the largest number.
Look at the choices of the following players and see which choice would maximize their gains  and then use those choices to make mine.

The game was always the same. I had to look at the last player's options to see which choice he/she would choose  and based on this information  the obvious choice for each player before the last player eventually led to the best choice for me. This strategy only worked because the last player's choice was always easily determined -- the last player always had the highest two numbers in the same row  so there was no real risk involved for them.
